04430nam a22006375i 9780822383451DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20022002ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223834517 a10.1515/97808223834512doi  a(DE-B1597)553649  a(OCoLC)1226680262  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aGT497.C6bF37 2002 7aSOC0050002bisacsh04a394.109512231 aFarquhar, Judith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAppetites :bFood and Sex in Post-Socialist China /cJudith Farquhar; ed. by John L. Comaroff, Arjun Appadurai. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (354 p.) :b12 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBody, Commodity, Text : 2100tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Eating: a politics of the senses -- tPreamble to Part I, Lei Feng, Tireless Servant of the People -- t1. Medicinal Meals -- t2. A Feast for the Mind -- t3. Excess and Deficiency -- tPart II. Desiring: an ethics of embodiment -- tPreamble to Part II, Du Wanxiang, The Rosy Glow of the Good Communist -- t4. Writing the Self: The Romance of the Personal -- t5. Sexual Science: The Representation of Behavior -- t6. Ars Erotica -- tConclusion, Hailing Historical Bodies -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJudith Farquhar’s innovative study of medicine and popular culture in modern China reveals the thoroughly political and historical character of pleasure. Ranging over a variety of cultural terrains--fiction, medical texts, film and television, journalism, and observations of clinics and urban daily life in Beijing—Appetites challenges the assumption that the mundane enjoyments of bodily life are natural and unvarying. Farquhar analyzes modern Chinese reflections on embodied existence to show how contemporary appetites are grounded in history.From eating well in improving economic times to memories of the late 1950s famine, from the flavors of traditional Chinese medicine to modernity’s private sexual passions, this book argues that embodiment in all its forms must be invented and sustained in public reflections about personal and national life. As much at home in science studies and social theory as in the details of life in Beijing, this account uses anthropology, cultural studies, and literary criticism to read contemporary Chinese life in a materialist and reflexive mode. For both Maoist and market reform periods, this is a story of high culture in appetites, desire in collective life, and politics in the body and its dispositions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEthnology. 0aFood habitszChina. 0aFood habits. 0aHuman bodyxSocial aspectszChina. 0aMedicinezChina. 0aMedicine, Chinese. 0aSex customszChina. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Customs & Traditions.2bisacsh1 aAppadurai, Arjun, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aComaroff, John L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822383451zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822383451423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822383451/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles